1345","1381":"1381","3 August 1381":"3 August 1381","1347":"1347","1445":"1445","1412":"1412","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1389":"1389","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1388":"1388","1387":"1387","1431":"1431","1318":"1318","Hopton, Suffolk, England":"Hopton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Whitehall St Ambrose, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"St Ambrose's Church, Whitehall, Bristol, England, United Kingdom","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Yonge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Dutch   De Jonge  , a variant of   De Jong  .","English: variant of   Young  ."],"variants":[{"name":"De Jonge","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Gerrit, Adriaan, Frans, Geert, Hendrik, Jacobus, Joop, Marinus, Marten, Maurits, Nicolaas, Pieter.  German Erna, Hans, Kurt.","Dutch and Flemish: variant of   De Jong  . This surname is also found in Germany."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Yonge was born about 1345, in Bristol, Gloucestershire, England, her father, Thomas Yonge, was 25 and her mother, Isold Hawberke, was 28. She married Walter Hopton in 1361, in Hopton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died on 3 August 1381, in her hometown, at the age of 37, and was buried in St Ambrose's Church, Whitehall, Bristol, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1345–3 August 1381":"umbes 1345–3. august 1381","1345–1381":"1345–1381","1346–1431":"1346–1431","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1335–1412":"1335–1412","1362–1387":"1362–1387","1388–1445":"1388–1445","1322–1389":"1322–1389","1318–1400":"1318–1400","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","Abt 1345":"umbes 1345","1381":"1381","3 August 1381":"3. august 1381","1347":"1347","1445":"1445","1412":"1412","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1389":"1389","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1388":"1388","1387":"1387","1431":"1431","1318":"1318","Hopton, Suffolk, England":"Hopton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whitehall St Ambrose, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"St Ambrose's Church, Whitehall, Bristol, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Shropshire, Engla